membership in the "community of the realm".This book traces the origins and growth of his cult, arguing that, especially after Edward's death, George came to represent a "good" politics (in this case, the shared prosecution of a war with spoils for everyone) and could beused to rebuke subsequent kings for their poor governance. Most kings came to realize this fact, and venerated St. George in order to prove their worthiness to hold their office. This political dimension of the cult never completely displaced the devotional one, but it was so strong that St. George survived the Reformation as a national symbol - one that grows ever more important in the wake of devolution and the recovery of a specifically English identity. JONATHAN GOOD is Associate Professor of History at Reinhardt College.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and politicsxHistory. 4aHeraldry & Genealogy. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCommunity of the realm.  aCult of St George.  aDevotional.  aEdward III.  aMedieval England.  aNational symbol.  aPatron saint.  aPolitical dimension.  aPolitical symbol.  aReformation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846157127?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846157127423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846157127/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles